As an AI language model, I can provide you with a general guide on how to write a program to create an encyclopedia using Go (Golang).

1. Define the data structure: Define the data structure that will hold all the information in the encyclopedia. You can use a map data type to store the key-value pairs of the entries.

2. Create a function to add entries: Create a function that will allow users to add new entries to the encyclopedia. This function should prompt the user to enter the title of the entry and its content. The function should then add the entry to the map data structure.

3. Create a function to search entries: Create a function that allows users to search for entries in the encyclopedia. This function should prompt the user to enter a search term and then search through the entries for any that match the term. The function should then display the matching entries.

4. Create a function to display all entries: Create a function that displays all the entries in the encyclopedia. This function should iterate through the map data structure and display the title and content of each entry.

5. Create a main function: Create a main function that will initialize the map data structure and call the other functions as needed. This function should present a menu of options to the user (such as add a new entry, search for an entry, or display all entries) and then call the appropriate function based on the user's choice.

Here is some sample code to give you a general idea:

```
package main

import "fmt"

// define the data structure
var encyclopedia = make(map[string]string)

// function to add entries
func addEntry() {
    var title, content string
    fmt.Print("Enter title: ")
    fmt.Scanln(&title)
    fmt.Print("Enter content: ")
    fmt.Scanln(&content)
    encyclopedia[title] = content
}

// function to search entries
func searchEntry() {
    var search string
    fmt.Print("Enter search term: ")
    fmt.Scanln(&search)
    for title, content := range encyclopedia {
        if contains(content, search) {
            fmt.Println(title, ": ", content)
        }
    }
}

// function to display all entries
func displayEntries() {
    for title, content := range encyclopedia {
        fmt.Println(title, ": ", content)
    }
}

// main function
func main() {
    for {
        fmt.Println("Encyclopedia Options:")
        fmt.Println("1. Add a new entry")
        fmt.Println("2. Search for an entry")
        fmt.Println("3. Display all entries")
        fmt.Println("4. Exit")
        var choice int
        fmt.Scanln(&choice)
        switch choice {
        case 1:
            addEntry()
        case 2:
            searchEntry()
        case 3:
            displayEntries()
        case 4:
            return
        default:
            fmt.Println("Invalid choice")
        }
    }
}

// helper function to check if a string contains a substring
func contains(s, substr string) bool {
    return len(s) >= len(substr) && s[:len(substr)] == substr
}
```

Please note that this is just a sample code and you may need to modify it to suit your specific requirements.
